{"title_page": "Umbuygamu language", "text_new": "{{Infobox language\n|name        = Umbuygamu\n|altname     = Morrobalama \n|states      = [[Australia]]\n|region      = [[Queensland]]\n|ethnicity   = [[Lama Lama people|Lamalama]], possibly [[Barungguan]]\n|extinct     = ?\n|familycolor = Australian\n|fam1        = [[Pama\u2013Nyungan languages|Pama\u2013Nyungan]]\n|fam2        = [[Paman languages|Paman]]\n|fam3        = [[Lamalamic languages|Lamalamic]]\n|iso3        = umg\n|glotto=umbu1256\n|glottorefname=Umbuygamu\n|aiatsis=Y55\n}}\n\n'''Umbuygamu''', or '''Morrobalama''' (Morrobolam), is an extinct [[Paman languages|Paman language]] from [[Princess Charlotte Bay]] in far-north [[Queensland]].\n\n== History ==\nIn 1898, the aboriginal population of the [[Princess Charlotte Bay]] numbered around 1,000. However, white settlement of the region caused them to lose almost all of their traditional lands. The many Aboriginal groups of the region were forcibly moved to missions and were exposed to diseases like syphilis and Spanish influenza. This resulted in the Aboriginal population of the region declining by 90% from 1898 levels. In the 1930s many of the surviving Aborigines were moved to the Old Lockhart Mission. Those Aborigines who remained in their territory were from the Morrobalama, Lamalama, and Umbindhamu tribes, and lived there until 1961. During that time, most of the Aborigines worked on local cattle stations or were killed by mounted police. In 1961 the Aborigines who had remained on their lands were moved to the tip of the Cape York Peninsula. By the 1990s, the total number of speakers was reduced to four elderly speakers. Only two of those speakers, Nancy Gunnawarra and Mabel Kullakulla, spoke the language on a regular basis. Most younger people of the community could understand the language but were unable to speak it.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== Phonology ==\n\n=== Vowels ===\nUmbuygamu's vowel system is typical of Australian Aboriginal languages in that it contains only five vowels.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite journal|last=Sarah|first=Ogilvie|date=1994|title=The Morrobalama (Umbuygamu) language of Cape York Peninsula, Australia|url=https://openresearch-repository.anu.edu.au/handle/1885/110346|language=en-AU|doi=10.25911/5d7638746d386}}</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|+\nVowels\n!\n!Front\n!Back\n|-\n!Close\n|i\n|u\n|-\n!Close-mid\n|e\n|o\n|-\n!Open\n|a\n|\n|}\nAll vowels show contrastive vowel length.\n\n=== Consonants ===\nUnusually for an Australian language, Umbuygamu has a relatively large consonantal inventory, including fricatives, prestopped consonants, and other consonants not normally found in Aboriginal languages.<ref name=\":0\" />\nIn this table, the orthographic symbols are bolded where they differ from IPA orthography.\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|+Consonants\n! colspan=\"2\" rowspan=\"2\" |\n! colspan=\"2\" |[[Bilabial consonant|Bilabial]]\n! colspan=\"2\" |[[Dental consonant|Dental]]\n! colspan=\"2\" |[[Alveolar consonant|Alveolar]]\n! rowspan=\"2\" |[[Postalveolar consonant|Postalveolar]]\n! rowspan=\"2\" |[[Retroflex consonant|Retroflex]]\n! rowspan=\"2\" |[[Palatal consonant|Palatal]]\n! colspan=\"2\" |[[Velar consonant|Velar]]\n! rowspan=\"2\" |[[Glottal consonant|Glottal]]\n|-\n!<small>plain</small>\n![[Pre-stopped consonant|<small>prestopped</small>]]\n!<small>plain</small>\n![[Pre-stopped consonant|<small>prestopped</small>]]\n!<small>plain</small>\n![[Pre-stopped consonant|<small>prestopped</small>]]\n!<small>plain</small>\n![[Pre-stopped consonant|<small>prestopped</small>]]\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\" |[[Stop consonant|Stop]]\n!<small>voiceless</small>\n|p\n|\n|'''tt''' /t\u032a/\n|\n|t\n|\n|\n|\n|'''tj''' /c/\n|k\n|\n|'''<nowiki/>'''' /\u0294/\n|-\n![[Voice (phonetics)|<small>voiced</small>]]\n|b\n|\n|'''dd''' /d\u032a/\n|\n|d\n|\n|\n|\n|'''dj''' /\u025f/\n|g\n|\n|\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\" |[[Fricative consonant|Fricative]]\n!<small>voiceless</small>\n|'''f''' /\u03b2/\n|\n|'''th''' /\u03b8/\n|\n|\n|\n|'''sh''' /\u0283/\n|\n|\n|'''h''' /x/\n|\n|\n|-\n![[Voice (phonetics)|<small>voiced</small>]]\n|'''v''' /\u00f0/\n|\n|'''dh''' /\u00f0/\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\" |[[Nasal consonant|Nasal]]\n!<small>voiceless</small>\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|'''kng''' /<sup>k</sup>\u014b/\n|\n|-\n![[Voice (phonetics)|<small>voiced</small>]]\n|m\n|'''pm''' /<sup>p</sup>m\n|\n|'''ttnh''' /<sup>t\u032a</sup>n\u032a/\n|n\n|'''tn''' /<sup>t</sup>n/\n|\n|\n|'''ny''' /\u0272/\n|'''ng''' /\u014b/\n|'''gng''' /<sup>g</sup>\u014b/\n|\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\" |[[Approximant consonant|Approximant]]\n!<small>plain</small>\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|'''y''' /j/\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n![[Lateral consonant|<small>lateral</small>]]\n|\n|\n|'''lh''' /l\u032a/\n|\n|l\n|\n|\n|'''rl''' /\u026d/\n|'''ly''' /\u028e/\n|w\n|\n|\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\" |[[Trill consonant|Trill]]\n!<small>voiceless</small>\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|'''rh''' /r\u0325/\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n![[Voice (phonetics)|<small>voiced</small>]]\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|'''rr''' /r/\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n! colspan=\"2\" |[[Flap consonant|Flap]]\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|'''r''' /\u027d/\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|}\n\n== Morphology ==\nUmbuygamu is an [[ergative\u2013absolutive language]].\n\n=== Nouns and Pronouns ===\nPersonal pronouns have two cases: nominative for intransitive and transitive subjects, and accusative for transitive objects. Nouns have an ergative case for transitive subject function and an absolutive case for intransitive subject and transitive object function. There are a total of at least 10 noun cases, and the case-marking suffix is dependent on the final consonant in the root word. The absolutive case is the only case suffix that is not final consonant-dependent, and has a zero as a suffix.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n'''atha -\u00d8           la-ngan'''\n\nfire-ABS        burn - 3sg0\n\n\"The fire is burning now.\"\n\nPronouns are attached to the end of the verb as a suffix, either as nominal or possessive.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Pama\u2013Nyungan languages|Paman}}\n\n[[Category:Paman languages]]\n[[Category:Extinct languages of the Northern Territory]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox language\n|name        = Umbuygamu\n|altname     = Morrobalama \n|states      = [[Australia]]\n|region      = [[Queensland]]\n|ethnicity   = [[Lamalama]], possibly [[Barungguan]]\n|extinct     = ?\n|familycolor = Australian\n|fam1        = [[Pama\u2013Nyungan languages|Pama\u2013Nyungan]]\n|fam2        = [[Paman languages|Paman]]\n|fam3        = [[Lamalamic languages|Lamalamic]]\n|iso3        = umg\n|glotto=umbu1256\n|glottorefname=Umbuygamu\n|aiatsis=Y55\n}}\n\n'''Umbuygamu''', or '''Morrobalama''' (Morrobolam), is an extinct [[Paman languages|Paman language]] from [[Princess Charlotte Bay]] in far-north [[Queensland]].\n\n== History ==\nIn 1898, the aboriginal population of the [[Princess Charlotte Bay]] numbered around 1,000. However, white settlement of the region caused them to lose almost all of their traditional lands. The many Aboriginal groups of the region were forcibly moved to missions and were exposed to diseases like syphilis and Spanish influenza. This resulted in the Aboriginal population of the region declining by 90% from 1898 levels. In the 1930s many of the surviving Aborigines were moved to the Old Lockhart Mission. Those Aborigines who remained in their territory were from the Morrobalama, Lamalama, and Umbindhamu tribes, and lived there until 1961. During that time, most of the Aborigines worked on local cattle stations or were killed by mounted police. In 1961 the Aborigines who had remained on their lands were moved to the tip of the Cape York Peninsula. By the 1990s, the total number of speakers was reduced to four elderly speakers. Only two of those speakers, Nancy Gunnawarra and Mabel Kullakulla, spoke the language on a regular basis. Most younger people of the community could understand the language but were unable to speak it.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== Phonology ==\n\n=== Vowels ===\nUmbuygamu's vowel system is typical of Australian Aboriginal languages in that it contains only five vowels.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite journal|last=Sarah|first=Ogilvie|date=1994|title=The Morrobalama (Umbuygamu) language of Cape York Peninsula, Australia|url=https://openresearch-repository.anu.edu.au/handle/1885/110346|language=en-AU|doi=10.25911/5d7638746d386}}</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|+\nVowels\n!\n!Front\n!Back\n|-\n!Close\n|i\n|u\n|-\n!Close-mid\n|e\n|o\n|-\n!Open\n|a\n|\n|}\nAll vowels show contrastive vowel length.\n\n=== Consonants ===\nUnusually for an Australian language, Umbuygamu has a relatively large consonantal inventory, including fricatives, prestopped consonants, and other consonants not normally found in Aboriginal languages.<ref name=\":0\" />\nIn this table, the orthographic symbols are bolded where they differ from IPA orthography.\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|+Consonants\n! colspan=\"2\" rowspan=\"2\" |\n! colspan=\"2\" |[[Bilabial consonant|Bilabial]]\n! colspan=\"2\" |[[Dental consonant|Dental]]\n! colspan=\"2\" |[[Alveolar consonant|Alveolar]]\n! rowspan=\"2\" |[[Postalveolar consonant|Postalveolar]]\n! rowspan=\"2\" |[[Retroflex consonant|Retroflex]]\n! rowspan=\"2\" |[[Palatal consonant|Palatal]]\n! colspan=\"2\" |[[Velar consonant|Velar]]\n! rowspan=\"2\" |[[Glottal consonant|Glottal]]\n|-\n!<small>plain</small>\n![[Pre-stopped consonant|<small>prestopped</small>]]\n!<small>plain</small>\n![[Pre-stopped consonant|<small>prestopped</small>]]\n!<small>plain</small>\n![[Pre-stopped consonant|<small>prestopped</small>]]\n!<small>plain</small>\n![[Pre-stopped consonant|<small>prestopped</small>]]\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\" |[[Stop consonant|Stop]]\n!<small>voiceless</small>\n|p\n|\n|'''tt''' /t\u032a/\n|\n|t\n|\n|\n|\n|'''tj''' /c/\n|k\n|\n|'''<nowiki/>'''' /\u0294/\n|-\n![[Voice (phonetics)|<small>voiced</small>]]\n|b\n|\n|'''dd''' /d\u032a/\n|\n|d\n|\n|\n|\n|'''dj''' /\u025f/\n|g\n|\n|\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\" |[[Fricative consonant|Fricative]]\n!<small>voiceless</small>\n|'''f''' /\u03b2/\n|\n|'''th''' /\u03b8/\n|\n|\n|\n|'''sh''' /\u0283/\n|\n|\n|'''h''' /x/\n|\n|\n|-\n![[Voice (phonetics)|<small>voiced</small>]]\n|'''v''' /\u00f0/\n|\n|'''dh''' /\u00f0/\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\" |[[Nasal consonant|Nasal]]\n!<small>voiceless</small>\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|'''kng''' /<sup>k</sup>\u014b/\n|\n|-\n![[Voice (phonetics)|<small>voiced</small>]]\n|m\n|'''pm''' /<sup>p</sup>m\n|\n|'''ttnh''' /<sup>t\u032a</sup>n\u032a/\n|n\n|'''tn''' /<sup>t</sup>n/\n|\n|\n|'''ny''' /\u0272/\n|'''ng''' /\u014b/\n|'''gng''' /<sup>g</sup>\u014b/\n|\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\" |[[Approximant consonant|Approximant]]\n!<small>plain</small>\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|'''y''' /j/\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n![[Lateral consonant|<small>lateral</small>]]\n|\n|\n|'''lh''' /l\u032a/\n|\n|l\n|\n|\n|'''rl''' /\u026d/\n|'''ly''' /\u028e/\n|w\n|\n|\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\" |[[Trill consonant|Trill]]\n!<small>voiceless</small>\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|'''rh''' /r\u0325/\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n![[Voice (phonetics)|<small>voiced</small>]]\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|'''rr''' /r/\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n! colspan=\"2\" |[[Flap consonant|Flap]]\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|'''r''' /\u027d/\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|}\n\n== Morphology ==\nUmbuygamu is an [[ergative\u2013absolutive language]].\n\n=== Nouns and Pronouns ===\nPersonal pronouns have two cases: nominative for intransitive and transitive subjects, and accusative for transitive objects. Nouns have an ergative case for transitive subject function and an absolutive case for intransitive subject and transitive object function. There are a total of at least 10 noun cases, and the case-marking suffix is dependent on the final consonant in the root word. The absolutive case is the only case suffix that is not final consonant-dependent, and has a zero as a suffix.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n'''atha -\u00d8           la-ngan'''\n\nfire-ABS        burn - 3sg0\n\n\"The fire is burning now.\"\n\nPronouns are attached to the end of the verb as a suffix, either as nominal or possessive.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Pama\u2013Nyungan languages|Paman}}\n\n[[Category:Paman languages]]\n[[Category:Extinct languages of the Northern Territory]]\n", "name_user": "Rodw", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguating links toLama Lama(link changed toLama Lama people) usingDisamAssist.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Umbuygamu_language"}
{"title_page": "2007\u201308 Serbian League West", "text_new": "{{Unreferenced|date=April 2010}}\n{{Infobox football league season\n | competition = [[Serbian League West]]\n | season      = 2007\u201308\n | prevseason = [[2006\u201307 Serbian League West|2006\u201307]]\n | nextseason = [[2008\u201309 Serbian League West|2008\u201309]]\n}}\n'''Srpska Liga West''' is a section of the [[Serbian League|Srpska Liga]], Serbia's third-tier football league. Teams from the western part of Serbia are in this section of the league. The other sections are [[Srpska Liga East]], [[Srpska Liga Vojvodina]], and [[Srpska Liga Belgrade]].\n\n==League table==\n{{#invoke:sports table|main|style=WDL\n|res_col_header=PR\n\n|team1=MLR|name_MLR=[[FK Mladi Radnik|Mladi Radnik]]\n|team2=SKR|name_SKR=[[FK Sloga Kraljevo|Sloga Kraljevo]]\n|team3=INON|name_INON=[[FK INON|INON]]\n|team4=MA\u010c|name_MA\u010c=[[FK Ma\u010dva \u0160abac|Ma\u010dva \u0160abac]]\n|team5=RKR|name_RKR=[[FK Radni\u010dki Kragujevac|Radni\u010dki Kragujevac]]\n|team6=SPM|name_SPM=[[FK Sloga Petrovac na Mlavi|Sloga Petrovac na Mlavi]]\n|team7=MKR|name_MKR=[[FK Metalac Kraljevo|Metalac Kraljevo]]\n|team8=JED|name_JED=[[FK Jedinstvo Ub|Jedinstvo Ub]]\n|team9=VVO|name_VVO=[[FK Vuji\u0107 Voda|Vuji\u0107 Voda]]\n|team10=BVA|name_BVA=[[FK Budu\u0107nost Valjevo|Budu\u0107nost Valjevo]]\n|team11=S\u010cA|name_S\u010cA=[[FK Sloboda \u010ca\u010dak|Sloboda \u010ca\u010dak]]\n|team12=U\u017dI|name_U\u017dI=[[FK Sloboda U\u017eice|Sloboda U\u017eice]]\n|team13=\u017dEL|name_\u017dEL=[[FK \u017delezni\u010dar Lajkovac|\u017delezni\u010dar Lajkovac]]\n|team14=MVP|name_MVP=[[FK Morava Velika Plana|Morava Velika Plana]]\n|team15=SBB|name_SBB=Sloga Bajina Ba\u0161ta\n|team16=\u016003|name_\u016003=[[FK \u0160umadija 1903|\u0160umadija 1903]]\n|win_MLR=24|draw_MLR=5|loss_MLR=1|gf_MLR=63|ga_MLR=17|status_MLR=C,P\n|win_SKR=16|draw_SKR=6|loss_SKR=8|gf_SKR=48|ga_SKR=31\n|win_INON=12|draw_INON=9|loss_INON=9|gf_INON=39|ga_INON=28\n|win_MA\u