f Serbia are in this section of the league. The other sections are [[Srpska Liga East]], [[Srpska Liga Vojvodina]], and [[Srpska Liga Belgrade]].\n\n==League table==\n{{#invoke:sports table|main|style=WDL\n|res_col_header=PR\n\n|team1=MLR|name_MLR=[[FK Mladi Radnik|Mladi Radnik]]\n|team2=SKR|name_SKR=[[FK Sloga Kraljevo|Sloga Kraljevo]]\n|team3=INON|name_INON=[[FK INON|INON]]\n|team4=MA\u010c|name_MA\u010c=[[FK Ma\u010dva \u0160abac|Ma\u010dva \u0160abac]]\n|team5=RKR|name_RKR=[[FK Radni\u010dki Kragujevac|Radni\u010dki Kragujevac]]\n|team6=SPM|name_SPM=[[FK Sloga Petrovac na Mlavi]]\n|team7=MKR|name_MKR=[[FK Metalac Kraljevo|Metalac Kraljevo]]\n|team8=JED|name_JED=[[FK Jedinstvo Ub|Jedinstvo Ub]]\n|team9=VVO|name_VVO=[[FK Vuji\u0107 Voda|Vuji\u0107 Voda]]\n|team10=BVA|name_BVA=[[FK Budu\u0107nost Valjevo|Budu\u0107nost Valjevo]]\n|team11=S\u010cA|name_S\u010cA=[[FK Sloboda \u010ca\u010dak|Sloboda \u010ca\u010dak]]\n|team12=U\u017dI|name_U\u017dI=[[FK Sloboda U\u017eice|Sloboda U\u017eice]]\n|team13=\u017dEL|name_\u017dEL=[[FK \u017delezni\u010dar Lajkovac|\u017delezni\u010dar Lajkovac]]\n|team14=MVP|name_MVP=[[FK Morava Velika Plana|Morava Velika Plana]]\n|team15=SBB|name_SBB=Sloga Bajina Ba\u0161ta\n|team16=\u016003|name_\u016003=[[FK \u0160umadija 1903|\u0160umadija 1903]]\n|win_MLR=24|draw_MLR=5|loss_MLR=1|gf_MLR=63|ga_MLR=17|status_MLR=C,P\n|win_SKR=16|draw_SKR=6|loss_SKR=8|gf_SKR=48|ga_SKR=31\n|win_INON=12|draw_INON=9|loss_INON=9|gf_INON=39|ga_INON=28\n|win_MA\u010c=12|draw_MA\u010c=7|loss_MA\u010c=11|gf_MA\u010c=30|ga_MA\u010c=27\n|win_RKR=11|draw_RKR=10|loss_RKR=9|gf_RKR=27|ga_RKR=24\n|win_SPM=11|draw_SPM=9|loss_SPM=10|gf_SPM=29|ga_SPM=32\n|win_MKR=11|draw_MKR=6|loss_MKR=13|gf_MKR=34|ga_MKR=32\n|win_JED=9|draw_JED=12|loss_JED=9|gf_JED=29|ga_JED=35\n|win_VVO=11|draw_VVO=5|loss_VVO=14|gf_VVO=37|ga_VVO=40\n|win_BVA=11|draw_BVA=5|loss_BVA=14|gf_BVA=23|ga_BVA=38\n|win_S\u010cA=11|draw_S\u010cA=4|loss_S\u010cA=15|gf_S\u010cA=32|ga_S\u010cA=40\n|win_U\u017dI=9|draw_U\u017dI=8|loss_U\u017dI=13|gf_U\u017dI=26|ga_U\u017dI=30\n|win_\u017dEL=9|draw_\u017dEL=7|loss_\u017dEL=14|gf_\u017dEL=25|ga_\u017dEL=38\n|win_MVP=8|draw_MVP=9|loss_MVP=13|gf_MVP=39|ga_MVP=41|status_MVP=R\n|win_SBB=9|draw_SBB=6|loss_SBB=15|gf_SBB=25|ga_SBB=36|status_SBB=R\n|win_\u016003=6|draw_\u016003=12|loss_\u016003=12|gf_\u016003=29|ga_\u016003=46|status_\u016003=R\n\n|col_P=green1|text_P=Promotion to the [[2008\u201309 Serbian First League|Serbian First League]]\n|result1=P\n|col_PP=green2|text_PP=Qualification for promotion play-offs\n|result2=PP\n|col_RP=red2|text_RP=Qualification for relegation play-offs\n|result14=RP\n|col_R=red1|text_R=Relegation to [[Serbian Zone League|Zone League]]\n|result15=R|result16=R\n|update=complete|source=\n}}\n\n{{Serbian League West}}\n{{2007\u201308 in Serbian football}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:2007-08 Serbian League West}}\n[[Category:Serbian League West seasons]]\n[[Category:2007\u201308 in Serbian football leagues|3]]\n[[Category:2007\u201308 in European third tier association football leagues|Serb]]\n", "name_user": "Jolicnikola", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eLeague table", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2007%E2%80%9308_Serbian_League_West"}
{"title_page": "City of Birmingham Stadium", "text_new": "{{short description|Proposed stadium in Birmingham, England}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox venue\n| stadium_name      = City of Birmingham Stadium\n| nickname          = \n| image             = \n| caption           = \n| location          = [[Saltley, Birmingham]], England\n| coordinates       = {{coord|52|28|50|N|1|51|46|W|type:landmark_region:GB|display=inline,title}}\n| broke_ground      = \n| opened            = TBA\n| closed            = \n| demolished        = \n| owner             = [[Birmingham City Council]]\n| operator          = [[Warwickshire County Cricket Club]]<br>[[Birmingham City F.C.]]\n| surface           = Grass\n| construction_cost = \n| architect         = \n| builder           = \n| former_names      = \n| tenants           = [[Birmingham City F.C.]]\n| seating_capacity  = 55,000\n}}\nThe '''City of Birmingham Stadium''' was a proposed [[multi-purpose stadium]] in the [[Saltley]] area  of [[Birmingham, England]], originally for [[Warwickshire County Cricket Club]] and [[Birmingham City F.C.]] to replace the current [[Edgbaston Cricket Ground]] and [[St Andrews (stadium)|St Andrews Stadium]] respectively.\n\nThe cricket club cancelled these plans however, and only the football club remained interested. The original proposal was the centrepiece of a larger scheme to create a \u00a3300 million sports village on a {{convert|60|acre|m2|adj=on}} site.<ref>''[http://icbirmingham.icnetwork.co.uk/mail/news/tm_method=full%26objectid=16815565%26siteid=50002-name_page.html  Blues chief reveals regeneration dream]'' \u2013 Birmingham Mail, 15 March 2006 (Accessed 10 March 2007)</ref>\n\nThe proposal was for a 55,000-seat arena was to be part-funded by [[Las Vegas Sands]], but the hopes of securing a licence for a [[super casino]] on site were rejected and Birmingham City F.C. were then unable to proceed with the plans for the stadium.<ref>[http://www.birminghammail.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/birmingham-citys-new-owners-open-123632 Birmingham City's new owners open talks over new stadium]</ref>\n\n==Setting==\nThe proposed stadium and sports village was to be located on a site currently occupied by [[Birmingham Wheels]] in the 'Wheels Adventure Park' of the [[Saltley]] area of Birmingham. The site is bounded by several active railway lines, a canal and numerous major roads.<ref>[http://www.digitalbrain.com/knhadriang98/web/City%20of%20Birmingham%20Stadium/000DF51B-5BCE-135F-A6F10C01AC1BF814.jpg Satellite image of the location with phase boundaries] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071027144037/http://www.digitalbrain.com/knhadriang98/web/City%20of%20Birmingham%20Stadium/000DF51B-5BCE-135F-A6F10C01AC1BF814.jpg |date=27 October 2007 }}</ref>\n\nIn relation to other areas, the site is near the St Andrews neighbourhood of [[Bordesley Green]] which is home to the [[St Andrews (stadium)|St Andrews Stadium]]. The stadium is to the southwest of the development. [[Small Heath, Birmingham|Small Heath]] is to the south whilst [[Nechells]] is located to the west and [[Aston]] to the north. It is 1.1 miles (1.77 kilometres) from [[Birmingham New Street railway station|Birmingham New Street station]] in the city centre.\n\nPhase 1 covers the Wheels Adventure Park and would have included the stadium within it. In terms of area, it was almost equal to that of Phase 2. Phase 1 would require the least amount of demolition as the land is largely untouched by development. The northern boundary of Phase 1 was determined by the [[Rugby-Birmingham-Stafford Line]] which serves the area via the nearby [[Adderley Park railway station]]. The western boundary was determined by another railway line and partially by a canal whilst the eastern boundary is determined by a road. Phase 2, to the south, is the separated from Phase 1 via the boundary of land owned by Birmingham Wheels. Within the phase would be a soccer dome, indoor arena, basketball courts, health and fitness centre, Olympic-sized swimming pool and an entertainment complex, which would be attached to the stadium.\n\nPhase 2 was the most southerly phase of the development and is a predominantly industrial site. Occupied by many workshops and warehouses, it required some of the most demolition needed for the project. This part of the sports village would have been home to community football pitches, tennis courts, residences, a hotel and large retail space. The southern and eastern boundaries are determined via roads and the small western boundary, via a railway line.\n\nPhase 3 was the smallest phase in terms of area and would have been used for the construction of residential properties and park land. The site is occupied by warehouses and workshops. It is separated through the centre via a road creating two thin strips of land which are bounded to the east by a canal.\n\nThe entire {{convert|60|acre|m2|adj=on}} site is contaminated as a result of heavy industry in the past and many of the buildings are derelict.<ref>[http://www.digitalbrain.com/knhadriang98/web/City%20of%20Birmingham%20Stadium/paper.jpg  Scan of newspaper article reporting the bid for the casino] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071027055549/http://www.digitalbrain.com/knhadriang98/web/City%20of%20Birmingham%20Stadium/paper.jpg |date=27 October 2007 }}</ref> It is believed the cost of decontaminating the land would be at \u00a31 million an acre.<ref name=\"18 May\">''[http://icbirmingham.icnetwork.co.uk/mail/news/tm_method=full%26objectid=19125215%26siteid=50002-name_page.html New super stadium a step closer]  {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110604053259/http://icbirmingham.icnetwork.co.uk/mail/news/tm_method%3Dfull%26objectid%3D19125215%26siteid%3D50002-name_page.html |date=4 June 2011 }}'' \u2013 Birmingham Mail, 18 May 2007 (Accessed 29 May 2007)</ref>\n\n==Design==\nThe new stadium would have been a multi-purpose 55,000-seater stadium<ref>[http://www.digitalbrain.com/knhadriang98/web/City%20of%20Birmingham%20Stadium/cob%20stadium.jpg Design specifications for the stadium] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071027143837/http://www.digitalbrain.com/knhadriang98/web/City%20of%20Birmingham%20Stadium/cob%20stadium.jpg |date=27 October 2007 }}</ref> which can host [[cricket]], [[football (soccer)|football]], [[Rugby football|rugby]] and concerts. It was proposed to include moving tiers of seating. It was planned for a supercasino to be built on site, however, after the council backed a separate bid at the [[National Exhibition Centre]] in [[Solihull]] which consisted of an 85,000 seater stadium to replace the former [[Wembley Stadium]].<ref>''[http://www.solihull-online.com/stadium.htm Birmingham has put in a bid for the National Stadium] \u2013 Solihull Online (Accessed 29 May 2007)</ref> Amongst other sites campaigning for the National Stadium were [[Coventry]].<ref>''[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/1507385.stm Coventry line up stadium shot]'' \u2013 BBC News, 24 August 2001 (Accessed 29 May 2007)</ref> However, London remained the preferred location for the Wembley replacement.<ref>''[http://www.london.gov.uk/mayor/wembley/wembley_es_article.jsp We cannot abandon Wembley now by Ken Livingstone] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070930205059/http://www.london.gov.uk/mayor/wembley/wembley_es_article.jsp |date=30 September 2007 }}'', 14 August 2001 (Accessed 29 May 2007)</ref> The bid for the sports village was pulled out by the council and it appeared dead.\n\nThe initial designs showed a stadium with an elliptical footprint and a sloping roof. This stadium was proposed to be built on [[Green belt (United Kingdom)|green belt]] land known as the [[Meriden Gap]], and not on the later chosen Wheels' Adventure Park. When the plans developed into more serious proposals, images of the new proposed stadium showed a stadium with a rectangular footprint and a large external framework.<ref>[http://www.digitalbrain.com/knhadriang98/web/City%20of%20Birmingham%20Stadium/birds%20eye%20view.jpg Bird's eye view of the stadium] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071003172053/http://www.digitalbrain.com/knhadriang98/web/City%20of%20Birmingham%20Stadium/birds%20eye%20view.jpg |date=3 October 2007 }}</ref><ref>''[https://www.bbc.co.uk/birmingham/content/articles/2005/10/26/super_sports_stadium_sport_feature.shtml Super sports stadium unveiled]'' \u2013 BBC Birmingham Sport (Accessed 29 May 2007)</ref> It was the only part of the sports village to have had a detailed design as the other buildings had not had full consideration.\n\nThe sports village would have included numerous facilities for sports as well as Birmingham's first [[Olympic size swimming pool]], however there were plans for an Olympic size swimming pool to be built at a site in [[Aston University]] near the [[Eastside, Birmingham|Eastside]].<ref>''[http://icbirmingham.icnetwork.co.uk/birminghampost/news/tm_method=full%26objectid=18708432%26siteid=50002-name_page.html US athletes to set up camp in Brum]'' \u2013 Birmingham Post, 5 March 2007 (Accessed 11 March 2007)</ref> As well as this, {{convert|9|acre|m2}} of the development could have formed a new community sports campus, on top of a 200-bed [[hotel]], an outdoor [[theatre]], approximately 2,500 new residential properties, a 170,000 square foot (15,793 m\u00b2) entertainment complex and large retail space.<ref>[http://www.digitalbrain.com/knhadriang98/web/City%20of%20Birmingham%20Stadium/plan%20view.jpg Masterplan showing the plan view of the sports village] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071026132753/http://www.digitalbrain.com/knhadriang98/web/City%20of%20Birmingham%20Stadium/plan%20view.jpg |date=26 October 2007 }}</ref><ref>[http://www.digitalbrain.com/knhadriang98/web/City%20of%20Birmingham%20Stadium/facilities.jpg The facilities at the Birmingham Sports Village] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071027055618/http://www.digitalbrain.com/knhadriang98/web/City%20of%20Birmingham%20Stadium/facilities.jpg |date=27 October 2007 }}</ref> An estimated total of 6,000 jobs will be created.\n\n==Planning history==\n===Campaign for a new stadium===\nPlans for a new stadium were aired as early as 2001 and it gained support from many football managers. [[Sven-G\u00f6ran Eriksson]] gave his support and the then-current chairman of [[Aston Villa F.C.|Aston Villa Football Club]], [[Doug Ellis]], announced that 47 of England's 92 league club chairmen had written to him backing the stadium.<ref>''[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/1576615.stm Eriksson 'backing' Birmingham stadium]'' \u2013 BBC News, 3 October 2001 (Accessed 10 March 2007)</ref> However, Ellis' support was subject to the venue becoming England's new national stadium. It was eventually overlooked for this honour in favour of a re-built [[Wembley Stadium]] in [[London]].\n\n===Plans develop===\nIt was revealed in late 2004 where the sports village would be located, however, not what the proposal would look like.<ref>''[http://icbirmingham.icnetwork.co.uk/post/news/tm_method=full%26objectid=14931060%26siteid=50002-name_page.html Revealed \u2013 Site for new super stadium]'' \u2013 Birmingham Post, 1 December 2004 (Accessed 10 March 2007)</ref> Immediately, [[David Gold (businessman)|David Gold]], chairman of Birmingham City F.C., submitted his support for the stadium.<ref>''[http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/b/birmingham_city/4060931.stm Birmingham target super stadium]'' \u2013 BBC News, 2 December 2004 (Accessed 10 March 2007)</ref><ref>''[http://www.footballeconomy.com/archive/archive_2004_dec_01.htm Give Us A Stadium, Gold Tells Brum]'' \u2013 The Political Economy of Football, 02/12/2004 (Accessed 10 March 2007)</ref> In March 2005, Birmingham City Council had a meeting to seek authority for the City Council to enter into an exclusivity agreement. Those at the meeting decided to implement the plan.<ref>[http://www.birmingham.gov.uk/xdirectory/public/MeetingTopics/viewTopic.jsp?recordId=21553 Birmingham City Council: Reports and Decision \u2013 City of Birmingham Stadium/Casino Exclusivity Agreement] (Accessed 29 May 2007)</ref> In May 2005, an image of the stadium was released however the full plans were not.<ref>''[http://icbirmingham.icnetwork.co.uk/birminghampost/news/tm_method=full%26objectid=15560556%26siteid=50002-name_page.html Revealed finally... Brum's \u00a3200 million super arena]'' \u2013 Birmingham Mail, 26 May 2005 (Accessed 10 March 2007)</ref> The council again held a meeting to answer and questions and to ease any concerns people had over the proposed stadium. There was confusion over whether this plans were for a new Birmingham City Football Club stadium or for a stadium for the city in general. Plans for two separate stadiums were even considered; one at the NEC and another on the Birmingham Wheels site.<ref>[http://80.86.36.120/vault/XDDocStore_3/0118570_m1392005.pdf ORDINARY MEETING OF BIRMINGHAM CITY COUNCIL \u2013 13 September 2005]{{dead link|date=August 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> The ambitious plans, designed by [[Populous (architects)|Populous]], were unveiled in October 2005 after talks between the council and [[Las Vegas Sands]].<ref>''[http://icbirmingham.icnetwork.co.uk/birminghampost/news/tm_method=full%26objectid=16295529%26siteid=50002-name_page.html\t Blues unveil stadium plan]'' \u2013 Birmingham Post, 26 October 2005 (Accessed 10 March 2007)</ref><ref>''[http://icbirmingham.icnetwork.co.uk/mail/news/tm_method=full%26objectid=16295551%26siteid=50002-name_page.html Unveiled \u2013 the \u00a3300m Blues gamble]'' \u2013 Birmingham Mail, 26 October 2005 (Accessed 10 March 2007)</ref>\n\nIn November 2005, a campaign for support for the stadium and super casino on site was launched.<ref>''[http://icbirmingham.icnetwork.co.uk/mail/news/casino/tm_method=full%26objectid=16359301%26siteid=50002-name_page.html  Campaign to win sports village support]'' \u2013 Birmingham Mail, 11 November 2005 (Accessed 10 March 2007)</ref><ref>''[http://football.guardian.co.uk/News_Story/0,,1643459,00.html Clubs queue up for a punt on super-casinos]'' \u2013 The Guardian Football, 16 November 2005 (Accessed 29 May 2007)</ref> An opinion poll revealed that over 80% were in favour and supportive of the project in the area. This came two months after local councillors said they would object the plan on moral and religious grounds.<ref>''[http://icbirmingham.icnetwork.co.uk/mail/news/tm_method=full%26objectid=16184125%26siteid=50002-name_page.html Setback for Blues casino plan]'' \u2013 Birmingham Mail, 28 September 2005 (Accessed 10 March 2007)</ref>\n\n===Stadium setback===\nHowever, on 20 March 2006 it was announced that the move would be unlikely to happen after [[Birmingham City Council]] announced plans to back the bid for a rival casino at the National Exhibition Centre, and not the one at the City of Birmingham Stadium. This was partly as a result of a petition handed to the council with 6,000 signatures from people in Saltley and [[Washwood Heath]].<ref>''[http://icbirmingham.icnetwork.co.uk/mail/news/casino/tm_method=full%26objectid=16683163%26siteid=50002-name_page.html Blues take on stadium protesters]'' \u2013 Birmingham Mail, 9 February 2006 (Accessed 10 March 2007)</ref><ref>''[http://icbirmingham.icnetwork.co.uk/mail/news/tm_method=full%26objectid=16678780%26siteid=50002-name_page.html 6,000 say no to Blues casino bid]'' \u2013 Birmingham Mail, 8 February 2006 (Accessed 10 March 2007)</ref> This backfired and claims from local councillors in 2005 that 84% of residents were supportive of the proposals.<ref>''[http://icbirmingham.icnetwork.co.uk/birminghampost/news/tm_method=full%26objectid=16679144%26siteid=50002-name_page.html Super casino fear for traders]'' \u2013 Birmingham Post, 8 February 2006 (Accessed 10 March 2007)</ref> However, it was revealed that the majority of the city were supportive of the proposals.<ref>''[http://icbirmingham.icnetwork.co.uk/mail/news/casino/tm_method=full%26objectid=16835972%26siteid=50002-name_page.html City majority backs Blues casino bid]'' \u2013 Birmingham Mail, 20 March 2006 (Accessed 10 March 2007)</ref> Rumours of the Birmingham City board trying once again to get the backing of the council have been spreading in the press, however nothing has been confirmed at this time.\n\nFor twelve months, there was little news of the plans except for Birmingham City Football Club saying there were still in talks with the council over the prospect of the Sports Village and stadium.<ref>''[http://icbirmingham.icnetwork.co.uk/mail/sport/tm_method=full%26objectid=18323495%26siteid=50002-name_page.html Blues still hoping for new stadium]'' \u2013 Birmingham Mail, 24 December 2006 (Accessed 10 March 2007)</ref><ref>''[http://icbirmingham.icnetwork.co.uk/birminghampost/news/tm_method=full%26objectid=17944669%26siteid=50002-name_page.html Olympic sports village may be priority for city]'' \u2013 Birmingham Post, 17 October 2006 (Accessed 10 March 2007)</ref>\n\n===The plans are reawakened===\nOne year later, after a period of little news, it was revealed that the late regeneration councillor at [[Birmingham City Council]], Councillor Ken Hardeman ([[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]] councillor for [[Brandwood (ward)|Brandwood]]), was to campaign to investors at the [[MIPIM]] show at [[Cannes]], [[France]] as part of Team Birmingham in March 2007.<ref>''[http://icbirmingham.icnetwork.co.uk/mail/sport/tm_headline=blues-revive-bid-for-new-stadium%26method=full%26objectid=18728742%26siteid=50002-name_page.html Blues revive bid for new stadium]'' \u2013 Birmingham Mail, 9 March 2007 (Accessed 10 March 2007)</ref>\n\nFollowing the MIPIM show, Ken Hardeman announced that the plans for the stadium were alive and that investors were interested in the stadium. However, there was no mention of the plans for a sports village raising uncertainty over whether they were no longer being assessed. Hardeman also revealed that the council were prepared to give {{convert|30|acre|m2}} of land they already own around the Birmingham Wheels site towards the project, creating an {{convert|80|acre|m2|adj=on}} site.<ref name=\"18 May\" />\n\n==Prominence==\nThe 55,000-seater stadium would have become the seventh largest football stadium in terms of capacity in England, behind [[Wembley Stadium]], [[Old Trafford]], [[London Stadium]], [[Tottenham Hotspur Stadium]] and [[Emirates Stadium]]. It would have been the largest football stadium in the city.\n\nThe sports village proposed for the city which will surround the stadium is similar to the Olympic Village proposed for the [[2012 Summer Olympics]] in [[London]], however on a smaller scale.\n\nThe [[supercasino]] which was proposed for the site along with the stadium was to become the first in the country. There had been mixed views over the submission of the bid for permission to build the casino on the site and it faced competition from other locations such as [[Blackpool]], [[Manchester]] and [[The O2 (London)|The O2]] in London with Manchester being the city selected to construct the supercasino.\n\nThe stadium would have been one of the most expensive developments in the city at an estimated \u00a3300 million. This is rivalled by the [[Bull Ring, Birmingham|Bullring Shopping Centre]], [[Snowhill]], [[Gateway Plus]], [[Arena Central]] and [[Martineau Galleries]].\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of English football stadiums by capacity]]\n* [[List of cricket grounds in England and Wales]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n{{Birmingham City F.C.}}\n{{Warwickshire CCC}}\n{{Proposed British Football Stadiums}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:City Of Birmingham Stadium}}\n[[Category:Birmingham City F.C.]]\n[[Category:Proposed football venues in England]]\n[[Category:Proposed stadiums in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Sports venues in Birmingham, West Midlands]]\n[[Category:Multi-purpose stadiums in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Defunct cricket grounds in England|Grounds]]\n[[Category:Proposed buildings and structures in Birmingham, West Midlands]]\n[[Category:Cricket in Warwickshire]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Proposed stadium in Birmingham, England}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2012}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2011}}\n{{Infobox venue\n| stadium_name      = City of Birmingham Stadium\n| nickname          = \n| image             = \n| caption           = \n| location          = [[Saltley, Birmingham]], England\n| coordinates       = {{coord|52|28|50|N|1|51|46|W|type:landmark_region:GB|display=inline,title}}\n| broke_ground      = \n| opened            = TBA\n| closed            = \n| demolished        = \n| owner             = [[Birmingham City Council]]\n| operator          = [[Warwickshire County Cricket Club]]<br>[[Birmingham City F.C.]]\n| surface           = Grass\n| construction_cost = \n| architect         = \n| builder           = \n| former_names      = \n| tenants           = [[Birmingham City F.C.]]\n| seating_capacity  = 55,000\n}}\nThe '''City of Birmingham Stadium''' was a proposed [[multi-purpose stadium]] in the [[Saltley]] area  of [[Birmingham, England]], originally for [[Warwickshire County Cricket Club]] and [[Birmingham City F.C.]] to replace the current [[Edgbaston Cricket Ground]] and [[St Andrews (stadium)|St Andrews Stadium]] respectively.\n\nThe cricket club cancelled these plans however, and only the football club remained interested. The original proposal was the centrepiece of a larger scheme to create a \u00a3300 million sports village on a {{convert|60|acre|m2|adj=on}} site.<ref>''[http://icbirmingham.icnetwork.co.uk/mail/news/tm_method=full%26objectid=16815565%26siteid=50002-name_page.html  Blues chief reveals regeneration dream]'' - Birmingham Mail, 15 March 2006 (Accessed 10 March 2007)</ref>\n\nThe proposal was for a 55,000-seat arena was to be part-funded by [[Las Vegas Sands]], but the hopes of securing a licence for a [[super casino]] on site were rejected and Birmingham City F.C. were then unable to proceed with the plans for the stadium.<ref>[http://www.birminghammail.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/birmingham-citys-new-owners-open-123632 Birmingham City's new owners open talks over new stadium]</ref>\n\n==Setting==\nThe proposed stadium and sports village was to be located on a site currently occupied by [[Birmingham Wheels]] in the 'Wheels Adventure Park' of the [[Saltley]] area of Birmingham. The site is bounded by several active railway lines, a canal and numerous major roads.<ref>[http://www.digitalbrain.com/knhadriang98/web/City%20of%20Birmingham%20Stadium/000DF51B-5BCE-135F-A6F10C01AC1BF814.jpg Satellite image of the location with phase boundaries] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071027144037/http://www.digitalbrain.com/knhadriang98/web/City%20of%20Birmingham%20Stadium/000DF51B-5BCE-135F-A6F10C01AC1BF814.jpg |date=27 October 2007 }}</ref>\n\nIn relation to other areas, the site is near the St Andrews neighbourhood of [[Bordesley Green]] which is home to the [[St Andrews (stadium)|St Andrews Stadium]]. The stadium is to the southwest of the development. [[Small Heath, Birmingham|Small Heath]] is to the south whilst [[Nechells]] is located to the west and [[Aston]] to the north. It is 1.1 miles (1.77 kilometres) from [[Birmingham New Street railway station|Birmingham New Street station]] in the city centre.\n\nPhase 1 covers the Wheels Adventure Park and would have included the stadium within it. In terms of area, it was almost equal to that of Phase 2. Phase 1 would require the least amount of demolition as the land is largely untouched by development. The northern boundary of Phase 1 was determined by the [[Rugby-Birmingham-Stafford Line]] which serves the area via the nearby [[Adderley Park railway station]]. The western boundary was determined by another railway line and partially by a canal whilst the eastern boundary is determined by a road. Phase 2, to the south, is the separated from Phase 1 via the boundary of land owned by Birmingham Wheels. Within the phase would be a soccer dome, indoor arena, basketball courts, health and fitness centre, Olympic-sized swimming pool and an entertainment complex, which would be attached to the stadium.\n\nPhase 2 was the most southerly phase of the development and is a predominantly industrial site. Occupied by many workshops and warehouses, it required some of the most demolition needed for the project. This part of the sports village would have been home to community football pitches, tennis courts, residences, a hotel and large retail space. The southern and eastern boundaries are determined via roads and the small western boundary, via a railway line.\n\nPhase 3 was the smallest phase in terms of area and would have been used for the construction of residential properties and park land. The site is occupied by warehouses and workshops. It is separated through the centre via a road creating two thin strips of land which are bounded to the east by a canal.\n\nThe entire {{convert|60|acre|m2|adj=on}} site is contaminated as a result of heavy industry in the past and many of the buildings are derelict.<ref>[http://www.digitalbrain.com/knhadriang98/web/City%20of%20Birmingham%20Stadium/paper.jpg  Scan of newspaper article reporting the bid for the casino] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071027055549/http://www.digitalbrain.com/knhadriang98/web/City%20of%20Birmingham%20Stadium/paper.jpg |date=27 October 2007 }}</ref> It is believed the cost of decontaminating the land would be at \u00a31 million an acre.<ref name=\"18 May\">''[http://icbirmingham.icnetwork.co.uk/mail/news/tm_method=full%26objectid=19125215%26siteid=50002-name_page.html New super stadium a step closer]  {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110604053259/http://icbirmingham.icnetwork.co.uk/mail/news/tm_method%3Dfull%26objectid%3D19125215%26siteid%3D50002-name_page.html |date=4 June 2011 }}'' - Birmingham Mail, 18 May 2007 (Accessed 29 May 2007)</ref>\n\n==Design==\nThe new stadium would have been a multi-purpose 55,000-seater stadium<ref>[http://www.digitalbrain.com/knhadriang98/web/City%20of%20Birmingham%20Stadium/cob%20stadium.jpg Design specifications for the stadium] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071027143837/http://www.digitalbrain.com/knhadriang98/web/City%20of%20Birmingham%20Stadium/cob%20stadium.jpg |date=27 October 2007 }}</ref> which can host [[cricket]], [[football (soccer)|football]], [[Rugby football|rugby]] and concerts. It was proposed to include moving tiers of seating. It was planned for a supercasino to be built on site, however, after the council backed a separate bid at the [[National Exhibition Centre]] in [[Solihull]] which consisted of an 85,000 seater stadium to replace the former [[Wembley Stadium]].<ref>''[http://www.solihull-online.com/stadium.htm Birmingham has put in a bid for the National Stadium] - Solihull Online (Accessed 29 May 2007)</ref> Amongst other sites campaigning for the National Stadium were [[Coventry]].<ref>''[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/1507385.stm Coventry line up stadium shot]'' - BBC News, 24 August 2001 (Accessed 29 May 2007)</ref> However, London remained the preferred location for the Wembley replacement.<ref>''[http://www.london.gov.uk/mayor/wembley/wembley_es_article.jsp We cannot abandon Wembley now by Ken Livingstone] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070930205059/http://www.london.gov.uk/mayor/wembley/wembley_es_article.jsp |date=30 September 2007 }}'', 14 August 2001 (Accessed 29 May 2007)</ref> The bid for the sports village was pulled out by the council and it appeared dead.\n\nThe initial designs showed a stadium with an elliptical footprint and a sloping roof. This stadium was proposed to be built on [[Green belt (United Kingdom)|green belt]] land known as the [[Meriden Gap]], and not on the later chosen Wheels' Adventure Park. When the plans developed into more serious proposals, images of the new proposed stadium showed a stadium with a rectangular footprint and a large external framework.<ref>[http://www.digitalbrain.com/knhadriang98/web/City%20of%20Birmingham%20Stadium/birds%20eye%20view.jpg Bird's eye view of the stadium] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071003172053/http://www.digitalbrain.com/knhadriang98/web/City%20of%20Birmingham%20Stadium/birds%20eye%20view.jpg |date=3 October 2007 }}</ref><ref>''[https://www.bbc.co.uk/birmingham/content/articles/2005/10/26/super_sports_stadium_sport_feature.shtml Super sports stadium unveiled]'' - BBC Birmingham Sport (Accessed 29 May 2007)</ref> It was the only part of the sports village to have had a detailed design as the other buildings had not had full consideration.\n\nThe sports village would have included numerous facilities for sports as well as Birmingham's first [[Olympic size swimming pool]], however there were plans for an Olympic size swimming pool to be built at a site in [[Aston University]] near the [[Eastside, Birmingham|Eastside]].<ref>''[http://icbirmingham.icnetwork.co.uk/birminghampost/news/tm_method=full%26objectid=18708432%26siteid=50002-name_page.html US athletes to set up camp in Brum]'' - Birmingham Post, 5 March 2007 (Accessed 11 March 2007)</ref> As well as this, {{convert|9|acre|m2}} of the development could have formed a new community sports campus, on top of a 200-bed [[hotel]], an outdoor [[theatre]], approximately 2,500 new residential properties, a 170,000 square foot (15,793 m\u00b2) entertainment complex and large retail space.<ref>[http://www.digitalbrain.com/knhadriang98/web/City%20of%20Birmingham%20Stadium/plan%20view.jpg Masterplan showing the plan view of the sports village] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071026132753/http://www.digitalbrain.com/knhadriang98/web/City%20of%20Birmingham%20Stadium/plan%20view.jpg |date=26 October 2007 }}</ref><ref>[http://www.digitalbrain.com/knhadriang98/web/City%20of%20Birmingham%20Stadium/facilities.jpg The facilities at the Birmingham Sports Village] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071027055618/http://www.digitalbrain.com/knhadriang98/web/City%20of%20Birmingham%20Stadium/facilities.jpg |date=27 October 2007 }}</ref> An estimated total of 6,000 jobs will be created.\n\n==Planning history==\n===Campaign for a new stadium===\nPlans for a new stadium were aired as early as 2001 and it gained support from many football managers. [[Sven-G\u00f6ran Eriksson]] gave his support and the then-current chairman of [[Aston Villa F.C.|Aston Villa Football Club]], [[Doug Ellis]], announced that 47 of England's 92 league club chairmen had written to him backing the stadium.<ref>''[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/1576615.stm Eriksson 'backing' Birmingham stadium]'' - BBC News, 3 October 2001 (Accessed 10 March 2007)</ref> However, Ellis' support was subject to the venue becoming England's new national stadium. It was eventually overlooked for this honour in favour of a re-built [[Wembley Stadium]] in [[London]].\n\n===Plans develop===\nIt was revealed in late 2004 where the sports village would be located, however, not what the proposal would look like.<ref>''[http://icbirmingham.icnetwork.co.uk/post/news/tm_method=full%26objectid=14931060%26siteid=50002-name_page.html Revealed - Site for new super stadium]'' - Birmingham Post, 1 December 2004 (Accessed 10 March 2007)</ref> Immediately, [[David Gold (businessman)|David Gold]], chairman of Birmingham City F.C., submitted his support for the stadium.<ref>''[http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/b/birmingham_city/4060931.stm Birmingham target super stadium]'' - BBC News, 2 December 2004 (Accessed 10 March 2007)</ref><ref>''[http://www.footballeconomy.com/archive/archive_2004_dec_01.htm Give Us A Stadium, Gold Tells Brum]'' - The Political Economy of Football, 02/12/2004 (Accessed 10 March 2007)</ref> In March 2005, Birmingham City Council had a meeting to seek authority for the City Council to enter into an exclusivity agreement. Those at the meeting decided to implement the plan.<ref>[http://www.birmingham.gov.uk/xdirectory/public/MeetingTopics/viewTopic.jsp?recordId=21553 Birmingham City Council: Reports and Decision - City of Birmingham Stadium/Casino Exclusivity Agreement] (Accessed 29 May 2007)</ref> In May 2005, an image of the stadium was released however the full plans were not.<ref>''[http://icbirmingham.icnetwork.co.uk/birminghampost/news/tm_method=full%26objectid=15560556%26siteid=50002-name_page.html Revealed finally... Brum's \u00a3200 million super arena]'' - Birmingham Mail, 26 May 2005 (Accessed 10 March 2007)</ref> The council again held a meeting to answer and questions and to ease any concerns people had over the proposed stadium. There was confusion over whether this plans were for a new Birmingham City Football Club stadium or for a stadium for the city in general. Plans for two separate stadiums were even considered; one at the NEC and another on the Birmingham Wheels site.<ref>[http://80.86.36.120/vault/XDDocStore_3/0118570_m1392005.pdf ORDINARY MEETING OF BIRMINGHAM CITY COUNCIL - 13 September 2005]{{dead link|date=August 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> The ambitious plans, designed by [[Populous (architects)|Populous]], were unveiled in October 2005 after talks between the council and [[Las Vegas Sands]].<ref>''[http://icbirmingham.icnetwork.co.uk/birminghampost/news/tm_method=full%26objectid=16295529%26siteid=50002-name_page.html\t Blues unveil stadium plan]'' - Birmingham Post, 26 October 2005 (Accessed 10 March 2007)</ref><ref>''[http://icbirmingham.icnetwork.co.uk/mail/news/tm_method=full%26objectid=16295551%26siteid=50002-name_page.html Unveiled - the \u00a3300m Blues gamble]'' - Birmingham Mail, 26 October 2005 (Accessed 10 March 2007)</ref>\n\nIn November 2005, a campaign for support for the stadium and super casino on site was launched.<ref>''[http://icbirmingham.icnetwork.co.uk/mail/news/casino/tm_method=full%26objectid=16359301%26siteid=50002-name_page.html  Campaign to win sports village support]'' - Birmingham Mail, 11 November 2005 (Accessed 10 March 2007)</ref><ref>''[http://football.guardian.co.uk/News_Story/0,,1643459,00.html Clubs queue up for a punt on super-casinos]'' - The Guardian Football, 16 November 2005 (Accessed 29 May 2007)</ref> An opinion poll revealed that over 80% were in favour and supportive of the project in the area. This came two months after local councillors said they would object the plan on moral and religious grounds.<ref>''[http://icbirmingham.icnetwork.co.uk/mail/news/tm_method=full%26objectid=16184125%26siteid=50002-name_page.html Setback for Blues casino plan]'' - Birmingham Mail, 28 September 2005 (Accessed 10 March 2007)</ref>\n\n===Stadium setback===\nHowever, on 20 March 2006 it was announced that the move would be unlikely to happen after [[Birmingham City Council]] announced plans to back the bid for a rival casino at the National Exhibition Centre, and not the one at the City of Birmingham Stadium. This was partly as a result of a petition handed to the council with 6,000 signatures from people in Saltley and [[Washwood Heath]].<ref>''[http://icbirmingham.icnetwork.co.uk/mail/news/casino/tm_method=full%26objectid=16683163%26siteid=50002-name_page.html Blues take on stadium protesters]'' - Birmingham Mail, 9 February 2006 (Accessed 10 March 2007)</ref><ref>''[http://icbirmingham.icnetwork.co.uk/mail/news/tm_method=full%26objectid=16678780%26siteid=50002-name_page.html 6,000 say no to Blues casino bid]'' - Birmingham Mail, 8 February 2006 (Accessed 10 March 2007)</ref> This backfired and claims from local councillors in 2005 that 84% of residents were supportive of the proposals.<ref>''[http://icbirmingham.icnetwork.co.uk/birminghampost/news/tm_method=full%26objectid=16679144%26siteid=50002-name_page.html Super casino fear for traders]'' - Birmingham Post, 8 February 2006 (Accessed 10 March 2007)</ref> However, it was revealed that the majority of the city were supportive of the proposals.<ref>''[http://icbirmingham.icnetwork.co.uk/mail/news/casino/tm_method=full%26objectid=16835972%26siteid=50002-name_page.html City majority backs Blues casino bid]'' - Birmingham Mail, 20 March 2006 (Accessed 10 March 2007)</ref> Rumours of the Birmingham City board trying once again to get the backing of the council have been spreading in the press, however nothing has been confirmed at this time.\n\nFor twelve months, there was little news of the plans except for Birmingham City Football Club saying there were still in talks with the council over the prospect of the Sports Village and stadium.<ref>''[http://icbirmingham.icnetwork.co.uk/mail/sport/tm_method=full%26objectid=18323495%26siteid=50002-name_page.html Blues still hoping for new stadium]'' - Birmingham Mail, 24 December 2006 (Accessed 10 March 2007)</ref><ref>''[http://icbirmingham.icnetwork.co.uk/birminghampost/news/tm_method=full%26objectid=17944669%26siteid=50002-name_page.html Olympic sports village may be priority for city]'' - Birmingham Post, 17 October 2006 (Accessed 10 March 2007)</ref>\n\n===The plans are reawakened===\nOne year later, after a period of little news, it was revealed that the late regeneration councillor at [[Birmingham City Council]], Councillor Ken Hardeman ([[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]] councillor for [[Brandwood (ward)|Brandwood]]), was to campaign to investors at the [[MIPIM]] show at [[Cannes]], [[France]] as part of Team Birmingham in March 2007.<ref>''[http://icbirmingham.icnetwork.co.uk/mail/sport/tm_headline=blues-revive-bid-for-new-stadium%26method=full%26objectid=18728742%26siteid=50002-name_page.html Blues revive bid for new stadium]'' - Birmingham Mail, 9 March 2007 (Accessed 10 March 2007)</ref>\n\nFollowing the MIPIM show, Ken Hardeman announced that the plans for the stadium were alive and that investors were interested in the stadium. However, there was no mention of the plans for a sports village raising uncertainty over whether they were no longer being assessed. Hardeman also revealed that the council were prepared to give {{convert|30|acre|m2}} of land they already own around the Birmingham Wheels site towards the project, creating an {{convert|80|acre|m2|adj=on}} site.<ref name=\"18 May\" />\n\n==Prominence==\nThe 55,000-seater stadium would have become the seventh largest football stadium in terms of capacity in England, behind [[Wembley Stadium]], [[Old Trafford]], [[London Stadium]], [[Tottenham Hotspur Stadium]] and [[Emirates Stadium]]. It would have been the largest football stadium in the city.\n\nThe sports village proposed for the city which will surround the stadium is similar to the Olympic Village proposed for the [[2012 Summer Olympics]] in [[London]], however on a smaller scale.\n\nThe [[supercasino]] which was proposed for the site along with the stadium was to become the first in the country. There had been mixed views over the submission of the bid for permission to build the casino on the site and it faced competition from other locations such as [[Blackpool]], [[Manchester]] and [[The O2 (London)|The O2]] in London with Manchester being the city selected to construct the supercasino.\n\nThe stadium would have been one of the most expensive developments in the city at an estimated \u00a3300 million. This is rivalled by the [[Bull Ring, Birmingham|Bullring Shopping Centre]], [[Snowhill]], [[Gateway Plus]], [[Arena Central]] and [[Martineau Galleries]].\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of English football stadiums by capacity]]\n* [[List of cricket grounds in England and Wales]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n{{Birmingham City F.C.}}\n{{Warwickshire CCC}}\n{{Proposed British Football Stadiums}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:City Of Birmingham Stadium}}\n[[Category:Birmingham City F.C.]]\n[[Category:Proposed football venues in England]]\n[[Category:Proposed stadiums in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Sports venues in Birmingham, West Midlands]]\n[[Category:Multi-purpose stadiums in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Defunct cricket grounds in England|Grounds]]\n[[Category:Proposed buildings and structures in Birmingham, West Midlands]]\n[[Category:Cricket in Warwickshire]]\n", "name_user": "Dawnseeker2000", "label": "safe", "comment": "MOS:DATEUNIFY (audit)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/City_of_Birmingham_Stadium"}
{"title_page": "Lamu-Lamu language", "text_new": "{{use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{use Australian English|date=March 2020}}\n{{distinguish|text= the [[Lama Lama people|Lamalama]] people}}\n\n{{Infobox language\n|name        = Lamu-Lamu\n|altname =Mba Rumbathama \n|states      = [[Australia]]\n|region      = [[Queensland]]\n|ethnicity   = [[Lama Lama people|Lamalama]]\n|speakers = 3\n|date=2016 census \n|ref=<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://stat.data.abs.gov.au/Index.aspx?DataSetCode=ABS_C16_T09_SA|title=Census 2016, Language spoken at home by Sex (SA2+)|publisher=ABS|website=stat.data.abs.gov.au|language=en-au|access-date=2017-10-30}}</ref>\n|familycolor = Australian\n|fam1        = [[Pama\u2013Nyungan languages|Pama\u2013Nyungan]]\n|fam2        = [[Paman languages|Paman]]\n|fam3        = [[Lamalamic languages|Lamalamic]]\n|iso3        = lby\n|glotto=lamu1254\n|glottorefname=Lamalama\n|aiatsis=Y136\n}}\n\n'''Lamu-Lamu''', or  '''Lama-Lama''', also known by the [[List of Australian Aboriginal group names|clan name]] '''Mba Rumbathama''', is a [[Paman languages|Paman language]] of [[Queensland]], [[Australia]].\n\nLamalama is one of four languages once spoken by the [[Lama Lama people|Lamalama]] people, the others being [[Umbuygamu language|Umbuygamu]], [[Mbariman-Gudhinma language|Mbariman-Gudinhma]], and [[Umbindhamu language|Umbindhamu]].<ref name=\"AIATSIS\" />\n\n==Further reading==\n*Verstraete, J. (2018). The Genetic Status of Lamalamic: Phonological and Morphological Evidence. Oceanic Linguistics 57(1), 1-30. University of Hawai'i Press. \n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Pama\u2013Nyungan languages|Paman}}\n[[Category:Paman languages]]\n[[Category:Extinct languages of Queensland]]\n", "text_old": "{{use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{use Australian English|date=March 2020}}\n{{distinguish|text= the [[Lamalama]] people}}\n\n{{Infobox language\n|name        = Lamu-Lamu\n|altname =Mba Rumbathama \n|states      = [[Australia]]\n|region      = [[Queensland]]\n|ethnicity   = [[Lamalama]]\n|speakers = 3\n|date=2016 census \n|ref=<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://stat.data.abs.gov.au/Index.aspx?DataSetCode=ABS_C16_T09_SA|title=Census 2016, Language spoken at home by Sex (SA2+)|publisher=ABS|website=stat.data.abs.gov.au|language=en-au|access-date=2017-10-30}}</ref>\n|familycolor = Australian\n|fam1        = [[Pama\u2013Nyungan languages|Pama\u2013Nyungan]]\n|fam2        = [[Paman languages|Paman]]\n|fam3        = [[Lamalamic languages|Lamalamic]]\n|iso3        = lby\n|glotto=lamu1254\n|glottorefname=Lamalama\n|aiatsis=Y136\n}}\n\n'''Lamu-Lamu''', or  '''Lama-Lama''', also known by the [[List of Australian Aboriginal group names|clan name]] '''Mba Rumbathama''', is a [[Paman languages|Paman language]] of [[Queensland]], [[Australia]].\n\nLamalama is one of four languages once spoken by the [[Lamalama]] people, the others being [[Umbuygamu language|Umbuygamu]], [[Mbariman-Gudhinma language|Mbariman-Gudinhma]], and [[Umbindhamu language|Umbindhamu]].<ref name=\"AIATSIS\" />\n\n==Further reading==\n*Verstraete, J. (2018). The Genetic Status of Lamalamic: Phonological and Morphological Evidence. Oceanic Linguistics 57(1), 1-30. University of Hawai'i Press. \n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Pama\u2013Nyungan languages|Paman}}\n[[Category:Paman languages]]\n[[Category:Extinct languages of Queensland]]\n", "name_user": "Rodw", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguating links toLama Lama(link changed toLama Lama people; link changed toLama Lama people; link changed toLama Lama people) usingDisamAssist.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lamu-Lamu_language"}
{"title_page": "Shellfish", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2013}}mum i lve yoy djarir p4 r6 (tughagucdg)rondkdk\n[[File:Oysters p1040741.jpg|thumb|right|Raw oysters opened and presented on a plate]]\n[[File:Cocktail 1 bg 060702.jpg|thumb|right|A [[shrimp cocktail]]]]\n'''Shellfish''' is a colloquial and [[fisheries]] term for [[exoskeleton]]-bearing [[Aquatic animal|aquatic]] [[invertebrate]]s used as [[food]], including various species of [[Mollusca|mollusc]]s, [[crustacean]]s, and [[echinoderm]]s. Although most kinds of shellfish are harvested from [[Seawater|saltwater]] environments, some are found in [[freshwater]]. In addition, a few species of [[land crabs]] are eaten, for example ''[[Cardisoma guanhumi]]'' in the [[Caribbean]].  Shellfish are among the most common [[food allergy|food allergens]].<ref>{{cite web | title = Shellfish Alergies | url = http://my.clevelandclinic.org/disorders/shellfish_allergies/hic_shellfish_allergies.aspx | publisher = [[Cleveland Clinic]] | accessdate = 2009-08-25}}</ref>\n\nDespite the name, ''shellfish'' are not actually [[fish]], but are simply water-dwelling animals. Most shellfish are [[Trophic level|low]] on the [[food chain]] and eat a diet composed primarily of [[phytoplankton]] and [[zooplankton]].<ref>{{cite web | title = Manual on the Production and Use of Live Food for Aquaculture | url = http://www.fao.org/docrep/003/W3732E/w3732e02.htm  | publisher = [[Food and Agriculture Organization of the United Nations]] | accessdate = 2009-08-25}}</ref> Many varieties of shellfish, and [[crustacean]]s in particular, are actually closely related to [[insects]] and [[arachnids]]; crustaceans make up one of the main [[Subphylum|subphyla]] of the phylum [[Arthropoda]]. Molluscs include [[cephalopods]] (squids, octopuses, cuttlefish) and [[bivalves]] (clams, oysters), as well as [[gastropods]] (aquatic species such as [[whelks]] and winkles; land species such as snails and slugs).\n\nMolluscs used as a food source by humans include many [[species]] of [[clam]]s, [[mussel]]s, [[oyster]]s, [[Periwinkle (mollusc)|winkle]]s, and [[scallop]]s. Some crustaceans that are commonly eaten are [[shrimp]], [[lobster]]s, [[crayfish]], and [[crab]]s.<ref>{{cite web | title = Shellfish climbs up the popularity ladder; the category is gaining chefs' attention for one-of-a-kind signature menu items | url = http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G1-85675992.html | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20121105143157/http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G1-85675992.html | url-status = dead | archive-date = 2012-11-05 | publisher = HighBeam Research | accessdate = 2009-08-25}}</ref> [[Echinoderm]]s are not as frequently harvested for food as molluscs and crustaceans; however, [[sea urchin]] [[roe]] is quite popular in many parts of the world, where the live delicacy is harder to transport.<ref>{{cite news|title=Sea urchin makes waves, popularity increases on American menus |url=http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_m3190/is_n34_v32/ai_21072930/ |archive-url=https://archive.today/20120524204135/http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_m3190/is_n34_v32/ai_21072930/ |url-status=dead |archive-date=2012-05-24 |publisher=[[Nation's Restaurant News]] via [[BNET]] |accessdate=2009-08-25 |first=Florence |last=Fabricant |year=1998 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=The sea urchin market in Japan |url=http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_m3089/is_n3_v51/ai_9071424/ |archive-url=https://archive.today/20120524204144/http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_m3089/is_n3_v51/ai_9071424/ |url-status=dead |archive-date=2012-05-24 |publisher=Marine Fisheries Review via [[BNET]] |accessdate=2009-08-25 |year=1989 }}</ref>\n\n==Terminology==\n[[File:Rheinische Muscheln.jpg|thumb|180px|right|Cooked [[mussel]]s]]The term \u201cshellfish\u201d is used both broadly and specifically. In common parlance, as in \"having shellfish for dinner\", it can refer to anything from clams and oysters to lobster and shrimp. For regulatory purposes it is often narrowly defined as filter-feeding [[molluscs]] such as clams, mussels, and oyster to the exclusion of [[crustacean]]s and all else.<ref>[http://textonly.mde.state.md.us/CitizensInfoCenter/FishandShellfish/harvesting_notices/index.asp Maryland Shellfish Harvesting Areas] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20061011102911/http://textonly.mde.state.md.us/CitizensInfoCenter/FishandShellfish/harvesting_notices/index.asp |date=11 October 2006 }}, Maryland Department of the Environment</ref>\n\nAlthough the term is primarily applied to [[Marine (ocean)|marine]] species, edible [[freshwater]] invertebrates such as [[crayfish]] and river [[mussels]] are also sometimes grouped under the umbrella term \"shellfish\".\n\nAlthough their shells may differ, all shellfish are invertebrates.  As non-mammalian animals that spend their entire lives in water they are \"fish\" in an informal sense; however, the term \u201dfinfish\u201d is sometimes used to distinguish [[fish]], animals defined by having [[vertebrate|vertebrae]], from shellfish in modern terminology.\n\nThe word \"shellfish\" is both singular and plural; the rarely used \"shellfishes\" is sometimes employed to distinguish among various types of shellfish.<ref>{{cite book | title=Fishermen: A Community living from the Sea | page=119 | last1=Festing | first1=Sally | year=1999 | location=Stamford | publisher=Shaun Tyas | isbn=978-1-900289-22-1 | edition=Revised}}</ref>\n\n==Shellfish in various cuisines==\nArchaeological finds have shown that humans have been making use of shellfish as a food item for hundreds of thousands of years. In the present, shellfish dishes are a feature of almost all the [[cuisine]]s of the world,  providing an important source of protein in many cuisines around the world, especially in the countries with coastal areas.\n\n[[File:Sakura ebi.jpg|thumb|180px|Sakura ebi ('cherry shrimp')]]\n\n===In Japan===\nIn the [[Japanese cuisine]], chefs often use shellfish and their [[roe]] in different dishes. [[Sushi]] (vinegared rice, topped with other ingredients, including shellfish, fish, meat and vegetables) features both raw and cooked shellfish.  [[Sashimi]] primarily consists of very fresh raw seafood, sliced into thin pieces. Both sushi and sashimi are served with soy sauce and [[wasabi]] paste (a Japanese [[horseradish]] root, a spice with extremely strong, hot flavor), thinly sliced pickled ginger root, and a simple garnish such as [[Perilla|shiso]] (a kitchen herb, member of the [[Mentha|mint]] family) or finely shredded daikon radish, or both.\n\n===In the United States===\n[[File:Boiled Maine Lobster.jpg|thumb|180px|left|Boiled [[American lobster|Maine lobster]]]]\n[[Lobster]] in particular is a great delicacy in the [[United States]], where families in the Northeast region make them into the centerpiece of a [[New England clam bake|clam bake]], usually for special occasions. Lobsters are eaten on much of the East Coast; the [[American lobster]] ranges from [[Newfoundland (island)|Newfoundland]] down to about the [[Carolinas]], but is most often associated with [[Maine]]. A typical meal involves boiling the lobster with some slight seasoning and then serving it with drawn butter, [[baked potato]], and [[corn on the cob]].\n\n[[Clam digging|Clamming]] is done both commercially and recreationally along the Northeast coastline of the US. Various type of clams are incorporated into the [[cuisine of New England]]. The soft-shelled clam is eaten either [[Fried clam|fried]] or [[New England Clam Boil|steamed]] (and then called \"[[soft-shell Clam|steamers]]\"). Many types of clams can be used for [[clam chowder]], but the [[quahog]], a hard shelled clam also known as a chowder clam, is often used because the long cooking time softens its tougher meat.\n\nThe [[Chesapeake Bay]] and [[Maryland]] region has generally been associated more with crabs, but in recent years the area has been trying to reduce its catch of [[Callinectes sapidus|blue crabs]], as wild populations have been depleted.  This has not, however, stemmed the demand: Maryland-style [[crabcake]]s are still a well known treat in crabhouses all over the bay, though the catch now comes from points farther south.{{Citation needed|date=January 2011}}\n\n[[File:Scallop sandwich (1).jpg|thumb|right|[[Scallop]] sandwich served in San Diego]]\nIn the [[Southeastern United States|Southeast]], and particularly the gulf states, [[shrimping]] is an important industry. Copious amounts of shrimp are harvested each year in the [[Gulf of Mexico]] and the [[Atlantic Ocean]] to satisfy a national demand for shrimp. Locally, prawns and shrimp are often deep fried; in the Cajun and Creole kitchens of [[Louisiana]], shrimp and prawns are a common addition to traditional recipes like [[jambalaya]] and certain stews. [[Crawfish]] are a well known and much eaten delicacy there, often boiled in huge pots and heavily spiced.{{cn|date=January 2020}}\n\nIn many major cities with active fishing ports, raw oyster bars are also a feature of shellfish consumption. When served freshly shucked (opened) and iced, one may find a liquid inside the shell, called the liquor. Some believe that oysters have the properties of an [[aphrodisiac]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2005/05/10/health/the-claim-oysters-are-aphrodisiacs.html|title=The Claim: Oysters Are Aphrodisiacs|last=O'Connor|first=Anahad|date=2005-05-10|work=The New York Times|access-date=2018-01-31|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\nInter-tidal herbivorous shellfish such as mussels and clams can help people reach a healthy balance of [[Omega-3 fatty acid|omega-3]] and omega-6 fats in their diets, instead of the current [[Western diets]].<ref>{{Cite journal |doi = 10.1038/4441002d|title = Shellfish view of omega-3 and sustainable fisheries|journal = Nature|volume = 444|issue = 7122|pages = 1002|year = 2006|last1 = Robson|first1 = Anthony}}</ref> For this reason, the eating of shellfish is often encouraged by dietitians.\nShellfish are also a rich source of the amino acid [[taurine]].\n\n==Around the world==\n[[File:Gambas in XXmiglia market.jpg| thumb|200px|Large shrimp or [[prawns]] for sale in Italy]]\n[[File:Cooked Snail Found In Rajang River.jpg|thumb|200px|A dish of cooked freshwater [[Neritidae|nerites]] from the [[Rajang River]], [[Sarawak]], [[Malaysia]]]]\nShellfish is a common part of indigenous cuisines throughout the Philippines.\n\nSome popular dishes using shellfish:\n* [[Ceviche]]\n* [[Cioppino]]\n* [[Callaloo]]\n* [[Clam chowder]]\n* [[Curanto]]\n* [[Fruits de mer]]\n* [[Paella]]\n* [[Sashimi]]\n* [[Shrimp cocktail]]\n* [[Lobster]] [[bisque (food)|bisque]]\n* [[She-crab soup]]\n* [[Sliced fish soup]]\n* [[Sushi]]\n* Shrimp [[Saganaki]]\n\n==Religious dietary restrictions==\n{{main|Jewish dietary laws}}\n\nThe [[Torah]] forbids the consumption of shellfish (i.e. the only permitted seafood is fish with fins and scales), in the books of [[Leviticus]] and [[Deuteronomy]].<ref>{{bibleverse||Leviticus|11:9-12|31}}</ref> Jews (of all religious traditions) who fully observe the dietary laws thus do not eat shellfish.  Neither do [[Seventh-day Adventist Church|Seventh-day Adventists]], who follow Jewish dietary law. Islamic schools of thought vary on whether (and which types of) shellfish may be acceptable. <ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.sistani.org/english/qa/01251/|title=Question and Answer: Meat}}</ref>\n\n== Allergy ==\nWhile estimates vary from shellfish, approximately 1% of the population is estimated to suffer from [[seafood]] allergy, which is more common in teenage and adult life than very early childhood. An estimated 20% will grow out of their [[allergy]] with time.\n\n== Toxic content ==\nSome shellfish, such as [[whelk]], contain [[arsenic]]. A sample of whelk was found to have a total content of arsenic at {{nowrap|15.42 mg/kg}} of which 1% is inorganic arsenic.<ref name=\"gov_fsis8205\">{{cite web|title=82/05 October 2005 Arsenic in fish and shellfish |url=http://www.food.gov.uk/multimedia/pdfs/fsis8205.pdf|date=2010-09-08|accessdate=2013-04-06|publisher=food.gov.uk}}</ref>\n\nShellfish caught in [[Alaska]] can lead to [[paralytic shellfish poisoning]] (PSP).<ref>http://dhss.alaska.gov/dph/Chronic/Documents/02-Internal/ParalyticShellfishPoisoningFactSheet.pdf</ref>\nPSP is caused by toxins released by [[dinoflagellate]], a type of algae, which are extremely poisonous (1000 times more potent than cyanide) and can lead to death by paralyzing the breathing muscles.\nDue to warming oceans algae blooms have become more widespread,<ref>https://www.theatlantic.com/science/archive/2018/12/north-pole-faces-unprecedented-climate-future-nasa-says/577915/</ref> thereby increasing the likelihood of intoxications of various types.\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Seafood]]\n* [[Seashell]]\n* [[Spotted trunkfish]] (also known as \"shellfish\" in many Caribbean countries) \n* [[Shellfish Association of Great Britain]] (SAGB)\n\n== References ==\n=== Citations ===\n{{Reflist}}\n\n=== Sources ===\n{{refbegin}}\n* [[Andrew Pawley|Pawley, Andrew]] (2004) [http://www.ling.mq.edu.au/centres/sc/june2004.htm \"Are crustaceans shellfish? A whiff of scandal in English lexicography\"] ''Australian Style'', '''12''' (1): 1\u20133.\n{{refend}}\n\n==External links==\n{{cookbook}}\n*[http://bcsga.ca/ BC Shellfish Growers Association]\n*[http://www.ecsga.org/ East Coast Shellfish Growers Association]\n*[http://pcsga.net/ Pacific Coast Shellfish Growers Association]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20060830083723/http://www.cefas.co.uk/Publications/shellfishnews/default.htm Shellfish News]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20090212213053/http://shellfish.org/image/tid/104 Shellfish Gallery]\n*[http://academic.evergreen.edu/t/thuesene/bivalves/Biology.htm#Biology Shellfish Guide]\n*[http://content.lib.washington.edu/cgi-bin/queryresults.exe?CISOOP=adv&CISORESTMP=%2Fsite-templates%2Fsearch_results-sub.html&CISOVIEWTMP=%2Fsite-templates%2Fitem_viewer.html&CISOMODE=