image = \n| caption = \n| discovery_ref = <ref name=\"MPC\">{{cite web | url=http://www.cfa.harvard.edu/iau/lists/NumberedMPs005001.html | title=Discovery Circumstances: Numbered Minor Planets (5001)-(10000) | accessdate=7 December 2008  | publisher=IAU: Minor Planet Center }}</ref>\n| discoverer = [[Carolyn S. Shoemaker]] and [[Eugene Merle Shoemaker]]\n| discovery_site = [[Palomar Observatory|Palomar]]\n| discovered = 1 January 1992\n| mpc_name = (8373) Stephengould\n| alt_names = 1992 AB\n| named_after = [[Stephen Jay Gould]]\n| mp_category = [[main-belt]]{{\u00b7}}{{small|([[Kirkwood gap|outer]])}}&thinsp;<ref name=\"jpldata\" /><br />2:1 res&thinsp;<ref name=\"Roig-2002\" />\n| orbit_ref = <ref>{{cite web | url=https://newton.spacedys.com/astdys/index.php?pc=1.1.0&n=8373 | title=(8373) Stephengould | accessdate=10 December 2008 | work=AstDyS | publisher=[[University of Pisa]] | location=Italy | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110526223143/http://hamilton.dm.unipi.it/astdys/index.php?pc=1.1.0&n=8373 | archive-date=26 May 2011 | url-status=dead }}</ref><ref name=\"jpldata\">{{Cite web |url=https://ssd.jpl.nasa.gov/sbdb.cgi?sstr=8373;cad=1 |title=8373 Stephengould (1992 AB) |work=[[JPL Small-Body Database]] |publisher=[[NASA]]/[[Jet Propulsion Laboratory]] |access-date=13 April 2016}}</ref>\n| epoch = 13 January 2016 ([[Julian day|JD]] 2457400.5)\n| aphelion = {{Convert|5.09996|AU|Gm|abbr=on|lk=on}}\n| perihelion = {{Convert|1.45970|AU|Gm|abbr=on}}\n| semimajor = {{Convert|3.27983|AU|Gm|abbr=on}}\n| eccentricity = 0.554947\n| period = 5.94 [[Julian year (astronomy)|yr]] (2169.6 [[Julian year (astronomy)|d]])\n| inclination = 40.7923\u00b0\n| asc_node = 88.8722\u00b0\n| mean_anomaly = 358.004[[Degree (angle)|\u00b0]]\n| arg_peri = 55.5019\u00b0\n| satellites = 1\n| dimensions = \n| albedo = \n| spectral_type = \n| abs_magnitude = 14.0\n| mean_motion = {{Deg2DMS|0.165931|sup=ms}} / day\n| rotation = {{Convert|4.435|h|d|abbr=on|lk=on}}\n| observation_arc = 8844 days (24.21 yr)\n| uncertainty = 0\n| jupiter_moid = {{Convert|1.4741|AU|Gm|abbr=on}}\n| tisserand = 2.587\n}}\n\n'''8373 Stephengould''' (1992 AB) is an [[Outer asteroid belt|outer main-belt]] [[binary asteroid]]<ref name=binary /> discovered on January 1, 1992, by [[Carolyn S. Shoemaker]] and [[Eugene Merle Shoemaker]] at [[Palomar Observatory]].<ref name=\"MPC\"/> The asteroid was named after the [[Harvard]] paleontologist [[Stephen Jay Gould]]. The asteroid has a very high inclination, having the second highest inclination of any of the first 10,000 discovered asteroids in the asteroid belt, after [[2938 Hopi]].\n\n''Stephengould'' is one of few strongly unstable asteroids located near the 2:1 [[Orbital resonance|mean motion resonance]] with the gas giant [[Jupiter]], that corresponds to one of the prominent [[Kirkwood gaps]] in the asteroid belt.<ref name=\"Roig-2002\" />\n\nThe asteroid has a moon orbiting it, discovered in 2010 with an orbital period of 1 day, 10 hours, and 9 minutes.<ref name=binary/>\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of minor planets]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|refs=\n\n<ref name=binary>{{cite web\n  |last1=Johnston\n  |first1=Robert\n  |title=(8373) Stephengould\n  |url=http://www.johnstonsarchive.net/astro/astmoons/am-08373.html\n  |website=johnstonsarchive.net\n  |accessdate=29 May 2015}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Roig-2002\">{{Cite journal\n  |first1     = F. |last1 = Roig\n  |first2     = D. |last2 = Nesvorn\u00fd\n  |first3     = S. |last3 = Ferraz-Mello\n  |date       = September 2002\n  |title      = Asteroids in the 2 : 1 resonance with Jupiter: dynamics and size distribution [ Erratum: 2002MNRAS.336.1391R ]\n  |url        = http://adsabs.harvard.edu/cgi-bin/bib_query?bibcode=2002MNRAS.335..417R\n  |journal    = Monthly Notices of the Royal Astronomical Society\n  |volume     = 335\n  |issue      = 2\n  |pages      = 417\u2013431\n  |bibcode    = 2002MNRAS.335..417R\n  |doi        = 10.1046/j.1365-8711.2002.05635.x\n  |access-date= 31 March 2017}}</ref>\n\n}} <!-- end of reflist -->\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.minorplanetobserver.com/pdolc/A8373_2004.HTM Lightcurve plot of 8373 Stephengould], Palmer Divide Observatory, [[Brian D. Warner|B. D. Warner]] (2004)\n* [https://books.google.com/books?id=2FNfjWKBZx8C&pg=PA165 Patrick Moore's Data Book of Astronomy], Cambridge University Press (2011)\n* [http://www.johnstonsarchive.net/astro/asteroidmoons.html Asteroids with Satellites], Robert Johnston, johnstonsarchive.net\n* [http://www.minorplanet.info/PHP/lcdbsummaryquery.php Asteroid Lightcurve Database (LCDB)], query form ([http://www.minorplanet.info/lightcurvedatabase.html info])\n* [https://books.google.com/books?id=aeAg1X7afOoC&pg Dictionary of Minor Planet Names], Google books\n* [http://obswww.unige.ch/~behrend/page_cou.html Asteroids and comets rotation curves, CdR] \u2013 Observatoire de Gen\u00e8ve, Raoul Behrend\n* [https://www.minorplanetcenter.net/iau/lists/NumberedMPs000001.html Discovery Circumstances: Numbered Minor Planets (1)-(5000)] \u2013 Minor Planet Center\n* {{AstDys|8373}}\n* {{JPL small body}}\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2019}}\n{{Minor planets navigator |(8372) 1991 VC2 |number=8373 |8374 Horohata}}\n{{Small Solar System bodies}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Stephengould}}\n[[Category:Background asteroids|008373]]\n[[Category:Unusual minor planets|008373]]\n[[Category:Discoveries by Carolyn S. Shoemaker]]\n[[Category:Discoveries by Eugene Merle Shoemaker]]\n[[Category:Minor planets named for people]]\n[[Category:Named minor planets]]\n[[Category:Binary asteroids|008373]]\n[[Category:Astronomical objects discovered in 1992|19920101]]\n\n\n{{beltasteroid-stub}}\n", "name_user": "AlanM1", "label": "safe", "comment": "replaced:   \u2013  \u2192 {{Snd}}  (2), NEODyS link fix, move {Use dmy dates} above infobox, fix mdy dates,MOS:UNITSYMBOLS, infobox list templates", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/8373_Stephengould"}
{"title_page": "Umbindhamu language", "text_new": "{{Infobox language\n|name        = Umbindhamu\n|states      = [[Australia]]\n|region      = [[Cape York Peninsula]], [[Queensland]]\n|ethnicity   = [[Umpithamu]], [[Lama Lama people|Lamalama]], possibly [[Barungguan]]\n|extinct     = likely by 2003\n|familycolor = Australian\n|fam1        = [[Pama\u2013Nyungan languages|Pama\u2013Nyungan]]\n|fam2        = [[Paman languages|Paman]]\n|fam3        = \n|iso3        = umd\n|glotto=umbi1243\n|glottorefname=Umbindhamu\n|aiatsis=Y50\n}}\n\n'''Umbindhamu''' (Umpithamu) is an extinct [[Australian aboriginal]] language of the [[Cape York Peninsula]], [[Queensland]], [[Australia]]. According to the Australian Indigenous Languages Database (AUSTLANG), there were two \"full speakers\" living in 2008.<ref name=AIATSIS/>\n\nAccording to Verstraete (2008:219), Umpithamu is 'one of four languages associated with a group of people currently known as Lamalama', the others being Morrobalama, Mba Rumbathama and Rimanggudinhma.<ref name=AIATSIS/>\n\n'Yintjinggu/Jintjingga' is a place name used for both Umbindhamu and the neighboring [[Ayabadhu language]].\n\n==Classification==\nThough generally accepted as a branch of the [[Paman languages]], Dixon believes it to be an [[language isolate|isolate]]. According to Rigsby (1997), Umbindhamu shares some grammatical features with the other languages spoken by the Lamalama people (Lamalama, Rimanggudinhma, and Morrobalama), but it shares more lexicon with [[Ayapathu language|Ayapathu]] and [[Umpila language|Umpila]].<ref name=\"AIATSIS\" />\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Pama\u2013Nyungan languages|Paman}}\n[[Category:Paman languages]]\n[[Category:Extinct languages of Queensland]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox language\n|name        = Umbindhamu\n|states      = [[Australia]]\n|region      = [[Cape York Peninsula]], [[Queensland]]\n|ethnicity   = [[Umpithamu]], [[Lamalama]], possibly [[Barungguan]]\n|extinct     = likely by 2003\n|familycolor = Australian\n|fam1        = [[Pama\u2013Nyungan languages|Pama\u2013Nyungan]]\n|fam2        = [[Paman languages|Paman]]\n|fam3        = \n|iso3        = umd\n|glotto=umbi1243\n|glottorefname=Umbindhamu\n|aiatsis=Y50\n}}\n\n'''Umbindhamu''' (Umpithamu) is an extinct [[Australian aboriginal]] language of the [[Cape York Peninsula]], [[Queensland]], [[Australia]]. According to the Australian Indigenous Languages Database (AUSTLANG), there were two \"full speakers\" living in 2008.<ref name=AIATSIS/>\n\nAccording to Verstraete (2008:219), Umpithamu is 'one of four languages associated with a group of people currently known as Lamalama', the others being Morrobalama, Mba Rumbathama and Rimanggudinhma.<ref name=AIATSIS/>\n\n'Yintjinggu/Jintjingga' is a place name used for both Umbindhamu and the neighboring [[Ayabadhu language]].\n\n==Classification==\nThough generally accepted as a branch of the [[Paman languages]], Dixon believes it to be an [[language isolate|isolate]]. According to Rigsby (1997), Umbindhamu shares some grammatical features with the other languages spoken by the Lamalama people (Lamalama, Rimanggudinhma, and Morrobalama), but it shares more lexicon with [[Ayapathu language|Ayapathu]] and [[Umpila language|Umpila]].<ref name=\"AIATSIS\" />\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Pama\u2013Nyungan languages|Paman}}\n[[Category:Paman languages]]\n[[Category:Extinct languages of Queensland]]\n", "name_user": "Rodw", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguating links toLama Lama(link changed toLama Lama people) usingDisamAssist.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Umbindhamu_language"}
{"title_page": "Umpithamu", "text_new": "{{use dmy dates|date=March 2017}}\nThe '''Umpithamu''', also once known to ethnographers as the '''Koko Ompindamo''', are a contemporary [[Indigenous Australian|Indigenous Australian people]] of the eastern [[Cape York Peninsula]] in northern [[Queensland]]. [[Norman Tindale]], transcribing their [[ethnonym]] Umpithamu as Umbindhamu, referred to them as a [[Band society|horde]] of the Barungguan.{{sfn|Tindale|1974}}\n\n==Language==\n[[Umbindhamu language|Umpithamu]] belongs to the [[Paman languages|Paman subgroup]] of the [[Pama\u2013Nyungan languages]].{{sfn|Verstraete|De Cock|2008|p=219}} By the early 2000s, there were only two complertely fluent speakers of Umpithamu, one of them being Mrs. Florrie Bassani.{{sfn|Verstraete|De Cock|2008|pp=217\u2013218}}\n\n==People and country==\nThe Umpithamu were the southernmost group of the [[Kawadji]] or 'sandbeach peoples' (in Umpithamu ''ma-yaandhimunu'' or 'people who own the sandbeach'.{{sfn|Rigsby|Chase|2014|p=307}}), followed in order to their north, by the [[Yintyingka]], the Umpila, the [[Pontunj|Pontunj (Yankonyu)]]{{sfn|Thomson|1933|p=255}}\nthe [[Pakadji|Pakadji(Koko Yao)]] and the [[Otati|Otati(Wuta(h)i]]).{{sfn|Rigsby|Chase|2014|p=308}} Their territory embraced an estimated {{convert|700|mi2|km2}} on the western coastline of [[Princess Charlotte Bay]] with its northern limits around Cape Sidmouth.{{sfn|Tindale|1974}}\n\n==History==\nFor some years in the 1950s a cattle station owner in Umpithamu territory had been complaining of the presence of this Indigenous people on his grazing lands, and after successful lobbying, he managed to have them removed in 1961. The Umpithamu were deported, reportedly by a ruse that deceived them, by the local police from their home country around [[Stewart River (Queensland)|Port Stewart]] to the [[Aboriginal reserve]] near [[Bamaga]], 400&nbsp;kilometres to their north. After decades they eventually managed to return south, to [[Coen, Queensland|Coen]], a mere 70&nbsp;miles from their tribal centre. Since then they have managed to set up three outstations in the Port Stewart area.{{sfn|Verstraete|De Cock|2008|pp=220\u2013221}} At present they form one of the several tribes groups composing the [[Lama Lama people|Lama Lama]] people.\n\n==Alternative names==\n* Baka (Kaantjuu term)\n* Banjigam (Bakanambia term)\n* Barungguan\n* Ganganda\n* Njindingga,\n* Umbuigamu//Umbindhamu\n* Yintjingga (native name of a place at mouth of Stewart River)\n\nSource: {{harvnb|Tindale|1974}}\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n===Citations===\n{{Reflist|20em}}\n\n==Sources==\n{{refbegin}}\n*{{Cite book| chapter = The Sandbeach People and Dugong hunters of Eastern Cape York Peninsula: property in land and sea country\n | last1 = Rigsby | first1 = Bruce\n | last2 = Chase | first2 = Athol\n | author1-link = Bruce Rigsby\n | year = 2014\n | title = Customary marine tenure in Australia\n | editor1-last = Peterson | editor1-first = Nicolas\n | editor2-last = Rigsby | editor2-first = Bruce | editor2-link = Bruce Rigsby\n | publisher = [[Sydney University Press]]\n | chapter-url = https://books.google.com/books?id=yr-6AwAAQBAJ&pg=PA311&lpg=PA311\n | pages = 307\u2013350\n | isbn = 978-1-743-32389-2\n | ref = harv\n}}\n*{{Cite journal | title = The Hero Cult, Initiation and Totemism on Cape York\n | last = Thomson | first = Donald F.\n | author-link = Donald Thomson\n | journal = [[The Journal of the Royal Anthropological Institute of Great Britain and Ireland]]\n | year = 1933 | volume = 63 | pages = 453\u2013537\n | doi = 10.2307/2843801 | jstor = 2843801\n | ref = harv\n}}\n*{{Cite book| chapter = Barungguan (QLD)\n | last = Tindale | first = Norman Barnett | year = 1974\n | author-link = Norman Tindale\n | title = Aboriginal Tribes of Australia: Their Terrain, Environmental Controls, Distribution, Limits, and Proper Names\n | publisher = [[ANU Press|Australian National University Press]]\n | chapter-url = http://archives.samuseum.sa.gov.au/tindaletribes/barungguan.htm\n | isbn = 978-0-708-10741-6\n | ref = harv\n}}\n*{{Cite journal | title = Construing Confrontation: Grammar in the Construction of a Key Historical Narrative in\n | last1 = Verstraete | first1 = Jean-Christophe\n | last2 = De Cock | first2 = Barbara\n | journal = Language in Society\n | date = April 2008 | volume = 37 | issue = 2 | pages = 217\u2013240\n | doi = 10.1017/s0047404508080275 | jstor = 20108123\n | ref = harv\n}}\n{{refend}}\n\n{{Aboriginal peoples of Queensland}}\n\n[[Category:Aboriginal peoples of Queensland]]\n", "text_old": "{{use dmy dates|date=March 2017}}\nThe '''Umpithamu''', also once known to ethnographers as the '''Koko Ompindamo''', are a contemporary [[Indigenous Australian|Indigenous Australian people]] of the eastern [[Cape York Peninsula]] in northern [[Queensland]]. [[Norman Tindale]], transcribing their [[ethnonym]] Umpithamu as Umbindhamu, referred to them as a [[Band society|horde]] of the Barungguan.{{sfn|Tindale|1974}}\n\n==Language==\n[[Umbindhamu language|Umpithamu]] belongs to the [[Paman languages|Paman subgroup]] of the [[Pama\u2013Nyungan languages]].{{sfn|Verstraete|De Cock|2008|p=219}} By the early 2000s, there were only two complertely fluent speakers of Umpithamu, one of them being Mrs. Florrie Bassani.{{sfn|Verstraete|De Cock|2008|pp=217\u2013218}}\n\n==People and country==\nThe Umpithamu were the southernmost group of the [[Kawadji]] or 'sandbeach peoples' (in Umpithamu ''ma-yaandhimunu'' or 'people who own the sandbeach'.{{sfn|Rigsby|Chase|2014|p=307}}), followed in order to their north, by the [[Yintyingka]], the Umpila, the [[Pontunj|Pontunj (Yankonyu)]]{{sfn|Thomson|1933|p=255}}\nthe [[Pakadji|Pakadji(Koko Yao)]] and the [[Otati|Otati(Wuta(h)i]]).{{sfn|Rigsby|Chase|2014|p=308}} Their territory embraced an estimated {{convert|700|mi2|km2}} on the western coastline of [[Princess Charlotte Bay]] with its northern limits around Cape Sidmouth.{{sfn|Tindale|1974}}\n\n==History==\nFor some years in the 1950s a cattle station owner in Umpithamu territory had been complaining of the presence of this Indigenous people on his grazing lands, and after successful lobbying, he managed to have them removed in 1961. The Umpithamu were deported, reportedly by a ruse that deceived them, by the local police from their home country around [[Stewart River (Queensland)|Port Stewart]] to the [[Aboriginal reserve]] near [[Bamaga]], 400&nbsp;kilometres to their north. After decades they eventually managed to return south, to [[Coen, Queensland|Coen]], a mere 70&nbsp;miles from their tribal centre. Since then they have managed to set up three outstations in the Port Stewart area.{{sfn|Verstraete|De Cock|2008|pp=220\u2013221}} At present they form one of the several tribes groups composing the [[Lama Lama]] people.\n\n==Alternative names==\n* Baka (Kaantjuu term)\n* Banjigam (Bakanambia term)\n* Barungguan\n* Ganganda\n* Njindingga,\n* Umbuigamu//Umbindhamu\n* Yintjingga (native name of a place at mouth of Stewart River)\n\nSource: {{harvnb|Tindale|1974}}\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n===Citations===\n{{Reflist|20em}}\n\n==Sources==\n{{refbegin}}\n*{{Cite book| chapter = The Sandbeach People and Dugong hunters of Eastern Cape York Peninsula: property in land and sea country\n | last1 = Rigsby | first1 = Bruce\n | last2 = Chase | first2 = Athol\n | author1-link = Bruce Rigsby\n | year = 2014\n | title = Customary marine tenure in Australia\n | editor1-last = Peterson | editor1-first = Nicolas\n | editor2-last = Rigsby | editor2-first = Bruce | editor2-link = Bruce Rigsby\n | publisher = [[Sydney University Press]]\n | chapter-url = https://books.google.com/books?id=yr-6AwAAQBAJ&pg=PA311&lpg=PA311\n | pages = 307\u2013350\n | isbn = 978-1-743-32389-2\n | ref = harv\n}}\n*{{Cite journal | title = The Hero Cult, Initiation and Totemism on Cape York\n | last = Thomson | first = Donald F.\n | author-link = Donald Thomson\n | journal = [[The Journal of the Royal Anthropol